# App Flow Document for Orange Meets

## Onboarding and Sign-In/Sign-Up

When a brand-new user launches Orange Meets, they are greeted by a simple landing page. This page, which is served from the initial load route (/routes/_index.tsx), checks immediately if a username is stored in the session cookies. If no username is found, the user is redirected to a dedicated page where they are prompted to enter a display name. This page (/routes/set-username.tsx) presents a clean form asking for the desired username. Once the display name is submitted and stored, the system directs the user back to the original meeting joining interface where further actions can begin. While there is no traditional sign-in or sign-up with email or social logins, the process of setting a display name serves as a lightweight account creation and identification step. Users may also clear their session or manually adjust the username through built-in debugging or settings options if needed.

## Main Dashboard or Home Page

After the onboarding process, the user reaches the primary interface for joining a room. The landing page now acts as a central entry point where users can input a meeting or room identifier. This page is cleanly designed with a form for entering a room name or ID. All necessary permissions such as camera and microphone access are requested as soon as a room is selected. After granting these permissions, users are transitioned to a meeting lobby. In this lobby page (/routes/_room.$roomName._index.tsx) the user sees a live preview of their camera and microphone feeds, and a display of current participants if any are already present. The interface is straightforward and organized, with clear buttons for joining the meeting or modifying device settings, making it easy for users to navigate to the full video conferencing experience.

## Detailed Feature Flows and Page Transitions

Once the user decides to join a room by clicking the join button on the lobby page, the application initiates several key processes. On entering the room, the system checks for required permissions and online status while using a custom hook (useUserMedia) to acquire the audio and video tracks. The application then establishes a WebSocket connection to a Cloudflare Durable Object responsible for managing room state. This connection is central to synchronizing actions such as muting, video toggling, or raising a hand with all other participants. The durable object, running on the backend as part of Cloudflare Workers, listens for connection events, messages, and periodic heartbeats to manage state and clean up inactive users. When the communication channel has been successfully established, the application uses PartyTracks to negotiate PeerConnections with other participants, fetches Ice server configurations, and sets up media streams through HTML elements that display video (via the VideoSrcObject component) and handle audio (via the AudioStream component).

As the meeting is in progress, users interact with a well-arranged video conferencing layout provided by the ParticipantLayout component. The main room page (/routes/_room.$roomName.room.tsx) presents all active video streams in a dynamic, responsive grid. Users have control over basic functionalities like toggling audio and video, engaging in screen sharing, and even raising their hand to grab the host’s attention. Additional interactive features include the ability to copy a unique meeting link for external invitations, and specialized control for enabling a data saver mode that hides other participants' video streams if needed. For those who opt for enhanced assistance, an AI assistant can be activated through a dialog (InviteAiDialog). On activation, a secondary PeerConnection establishes an interaction pathway with OpenAI’s service, allowing users to use push-to-talk controls (AiPushToTalkButton) and adjust the AI’s behavior with customizable settings. In meetings where real-time transcription is enabled, one designated participant automatically becomes the Transcription Host, receiving and processing audio streams to convert speech to text in real time through the use of web sockets and the OpenAI API.

## Settings and Account Management

Within the Orange Meets experience, users have access to settings that allow them to manage how they interact with the app. There is a dedicated settings dialog accessible from the meeting interface where users can modify camera and microphone settings, choose from different available devices, and configure specific features such as the AI assistant. These interface elements are designed to be intuitive and nonintrusive so that users can easily return to the main conference view after making adjustments. Although there is not a complete account management system in the traditional sense, session management via stored usernames and local preferences covers the essential requirements for recognition and personalized device usage throughout meetings. Transitions back to the main meeting room are seamless, ensuring that users continue their conversation without unnecessary interruptions.

## Error States and Alternate Paths

Orange Meets also robustly handles situations where errors or interruptions occur. If a user denies permission to access the camera or microphone, the application provides clear prompts and error messages that explain the need for such permissions before moving forward. Should the user enter an invalid room name or experience connectivity issues, fallback pages and notifications are displayed to guide them back to a corrective path. For example, if the WebSocket connection to the Durable Object fails or is interrupted, the system attempts to reconnect and informs the user of any temporary disruptions in service. In cases where restricted actions are attempted, such as toggling device settings during a critical operation, the user is presented with a friendly error message that directs them on how to properly resolve the situation before proceeding. These measures ensure that regardless of the error state, the user is never left uncertain about how to progress or recover from an issue.

## Conclusion and Overall App Journey

Orange Meets offers a smooth journey for every user, starting from a lightweight onboarding process that sets a display name, leading directly to a clean meeting join interface. In the lobby, users have the chance to preview and adjust their media settings before entering the live video conference, where a variety of interactive features are available. Once inside the room, the application takes care of all media negotiations and room state management via Cloudflare Durable Objects, while also offering advanced options like AI assistance and real-time transcription for those who need it. Whether a user is simply joining a meeting, tweaking individual device settings, or engaging with enhanced AI features, the entire application flow is designed to be clear, responsive, and resilient even in the face of errors. The system’s architecture ensures that every user action and interface transition is well connected, creating a comprehensive and reliable video conferencing experience.
